  "prompt": "What is the meaning of the phrase - 'majboori ka naam mahatma gandhi'?",
  "response": "The phrase \"majboori ka naam mahatma gandhi\" is a Hindi expression that translates roughly to \"Compulsion is called Mahatma Gandhi\" or \"Helplessness is named Mahatma Gandhi.\" \n\nIt is typically used sarcastically or humorously to suggest that someone is doing something out of necessity or compulsion, rather than by choice, and then trying to present it as a principled or noble action. The phrase implies that the person is justifying their actions by claiming they have no other option, similar to how Mahatma Gandhi was known for making difficult choices under challenging circumstances.\n\nThe saying essentially means that when someone is forced to do something they don't want to do, they might try to rationalize it by presenting it as a virtuous or unavoidable decision.",
